istrict.  For one, it makes for a better neighborhood and that affects housing values.  What Benedikt and Wong DON'T get (among other things) is: (1) if all of the private school students were to transfer to the public schools, there would be larger class sizes, higher student/teacher ratios, less ability for ANY of the students to learn, etc., (2) no amount of parent involvement or support will make it better,... it is not within their power to make it better.  It is within the power of the administrators and union of teachers to make it better by demanding standards of their membership, weeding out poor performers, rewarding high performers, and creating the environment where learning is paramount. (Funny thing, if THAT were done, those sending their kids to private school (and paying for two school systems) might be encouraged to put their kids in the public system.   Are parents who send their children to private schools doing a disservice to the public school system?  No.  Those who are on the taxpayer dole and are supposed to be managing and teaching in the public system are doing a disservice to the system they are supposed to be serving "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1460" language="en" documentId="4057" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Bill in LA" date="Aug 29, 2013 5:55PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="15" thumbsDown="0" origId="4057" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1460"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>